         = 233\n| elevation_ft            = \n<!-- population -->\n| population_as_of        = 2019-01-01<ref>{{cite web |title=Population of municipalities of the Czech republic|url=https://www.czso.cz/documents/10180/91917344/1300721903.pdf/ea01e710-2ae5-49f3-8792-ebb384754346?version=1.0|publisher=Czech Statistical Office|accessdate=2019-04-30}}</ref>\n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 19133\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_sq_mi=\n| population_demonym      = \n<!-- time zone(s) -->\n| timezone1               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +1\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +2\n<!-- postal codes, area code -->\n| postal_code_type        = Postal code\n| postal_code             = 438 01\n| area_code_type          =  \n| area_code               = \n| geocode                 = \n| iso_code                = \n<!-- website, footnotes -->\n| website                 = [https://www.mesto-zatec.cz/ www.mesto-zatec.cz]\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n[[Image:Zatec CZ Knezska brana PICT2989.jpg|256px|thumb|right|The Priests' Gate]]\n\n'''\u017datec''' ({{IPA-cs|\u02c8\u0292at\u025bts}}; {{lang-de|Saaz}}) is a historic town in [[Louny District]], [[\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem Region]], in the [[Czech Republic]]. \n\nIt is famous for an over-700-year-long tradition of growing [[Saaz hops|Saaz noble hops]] used by several breweries. \u017datec produces its own beer and hosts 'Do\u010desn\u00e1', its hops-related harvest festival every year on the town square.\n\n==History==\nThe  earliest historical reference to the [[Duchy of Bohemia|Bohemian]] fortress of ''Sacz'' is in the Latin chronicle of [[Thietmar of Merseburg]] of 1004, when King [[Henry II, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry II of Germany]] reconquered it from the Polish duke [[Boles\u0142aw I Chrobry]]. During the 11th century it belonged to the [[Vr\u0161ovci]] - a powerful [[Czechs|Czech]] aristocratic family. It received the privileges of a royal town under King [[Ottokar II of Bohemia]] in 1265. A coat-of-arms was given to the citizens by King [[Vladislaus II of Hungary|Vladislav II]] for their courage during the storming of [[Milan]].\n\nFrom the outbreak of the [[Hussite Wars]] in 1419 to the [[Thirty Years' War]], the town was [[Hussite]] or [[Protestant]], but after the [[Battle of White Mountain]] (1620) the greater part of the Czech inhabitants left the town, which remained [[German people|German]] and [[Roman Catholic]] until 1945, when the German speaking inhabitants were [[Expulsion of Germans from Czechoslovakia|forced to leave their home and expelled to Germany]]. On June 3, 1945 about 5,000 German inhabitants were gathered on the Market place and marched to [[Postoloprty]], where at least 763 were murdered in the [[Postoloprty massacre]], estimates range up to 2,000 victims killed by Czechoslovak military in \u017datec and on the March.<ref>[[https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-66696029.html Mord im Fasanengarten]], [[Der Spiegel]], 31 August 2009 (German)</ref>\n\nDuring and after the Second World War a [[Messerschmitt]] production facility and air base for testing aircraft, including new jet fighters, was located close to the town. In 1948 the production facility continued to produce the [[Avia S-199]], a version of the [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]] aircraft which were sold to [[Israel]], with the initial training for the Israeli pilots provided at the air base. Many other military supplies were flown to Israel from the air base, which helped the new state to secure its independence.\n\nThe Czech Culture Ministry sent the nomination of Zatec as the town of hops for listing among the world heritage to the UNESCO committee on 29/05/2007. Unfortunately within this round Zatec did not make UNESCO World Heritage Sites list, but it has been encouraged by the respective committee assessing nominations to try again.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radio.cz/en/section/news/zatec-fails-to-make-unesco-world-heritage-sites-list|title=\u017datec fails to make UNESCO World Heritage Sites list {{!}} Radio Prague|website=Radio Praha|language=en|access-date=2018-12-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, \u017datec was used as one of the locations for the [[92nd Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning film, [[Jojo Rabbit]].\n\n== People ==\n* [[Gabriel Anton]]\n* [[Peter Glaser]]\n* [[Eugen Gura]]\n* [[Petr Kotvald]]\n* [[Johannes von Tepl]]\n* [[Karel Reiner]]\n*[[Adolf Strauss (composer)|Adolf Strauss]]\n* [[Jan Sv\u011br\u00e1k]]\n* [[Zden\u011bk Sv\u011br\u00e1k]]\n* [[Maria Treben]]\n* [[Miroslav Varga]]\n* [[Marie Rumanov\u00e1]]\n\n==Twin towns \u2014 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in the Czech Republic}}\n\n\u017datec is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=Partnersk\u00e1 m\u011bsta|url=https://www.mesto-zatec.cz/mesto/partnerska-mesta/|publisher=M\u011bsto \u017datec|language=cs|accessdate=2019-08-23}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*{{flagicon|BEL}} [[Poperinge]], [[Belgium]]\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Thum]], [[Germany]]\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Krasnystaw]], [[Poland]]\n*{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Novocheboksarsk]], [[Russia]]\n*{{flagicon|SLO}} [[\u017dalec]], [[Slovenia]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Selibice (Sta\u0148kovice)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|\u017datec}}\n{{Wikisourcecat}}\n* [http://english.mesto-zatec.cz/ Official website] \n* [http://www.saaz.info/ Friends of Saaz/ \u017datec (in German and English)]\n* [https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/5153/ UNESCO on \u017datec \u2013 the Hops Town (English)]\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Saaz|short=x}}\n\n{{Louny District}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zatec}}\n[[Category:Cities and towns in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Louny District]]\n", "text_old": "{{not to be confused with|Zatec (Jihlava District)}}\n{{more footnotes|date=January